               <p>PHILIP HITCHINGS. On Saturday night, between ten and eleven o'clock, I lost a silk handkerchief in <placeName id="t18310908-338-crimeloc1742">Newportmarket</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-338-crimeloc1742" type="placeName" value="Newportmarket"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310908-338-crimeloc1742" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-338-off1740 t18310908-338-crimeloc1742"></join>, and found it at Bow-street; I knew nothing of the prisoner till I found her at the office.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-338-person2432">
                  JOHN 
                  GROOM
               <interp inst="t18310908-338-person2432" type="surname" value="GROOM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-338-person2432" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-338-person2432" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Chapel-street, Long-acre. On the 9th of July, between ten and eleven o'clock at night, I was in Newport-market, and saw the prisoner attempt a number of pockets; the prosecutor and his wife were looking at a butter-shop - she put her hand into his pocket, and took out a silk handkerchief; I went up and asked his address; when I had secured her I lost him - I afterwards got him to attend at the office; I am positive I saw the prisoner take the silk handkerchief from his pocket.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I picked it up.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310908-338-verdict1743" type="verdictDescription">
